Package org.vngx.jsch.hash

  • Interface Summary 
    Interface Description
    Hash
    Interface to define a cryptographic hash algorithm.
    MAC
    A MAC (message authentication code) algorithm, sometimes called a keyed (cryptographic) hash function, accepts as input a secret key and an arbitrary-length message to be authenticated, and outputs a MAC (sometimes known as a tag).
  • Class Summary 
    Class Description
    HashImpl
    Implementation of Hash providing a wrapper for Java's built in message digest algorithms.
    HashImpl.MD5
    Implementation of HashImpl using Java's MD5 message digest.
    HashImpl.SHA1
    Implementation of HashImpl using Java's SHA1 message digest.
    HashImpl.SHA256
    Implementation of HashImpl using Java's SHA-256 message digest.
    HashManager  
    MACImpl
    Implementation of MAC (Message Authentication Code) using the implementations provided by JCE.
    MACImpl.HMAC_MD5
    Implementation of MAC using MD5 for the hash.
    MACImpl.HMAC_MD5_96
    Implementation of MAC using the first 96 bits of MD5 hash.
    MACImpl.HMAC_SHA_256
    Implementation of MAC using the SHA-256 hash.
    MACImpl.HMAC_SHA1
    Implementation of MAC using SHA-1 for the hash.
    MACImpl.HMAC_SHA1_96
    Implementation of MAC using the first 96 bits of SHA-1 hash.
    MACImplAlternate
    Implementation of MAC algorithm (Message Authentication Code), provided as an alternative to Java's built in MAC implementations through JCE.
    MACImplAlternate.HMAC_MD5
    Implementation of MAC using MD5 for the hash.
    MACImplAlternate.HMAC_MD5_96
    Implementation of MAC using MD5 with a block size of 12.
    MACImplAlternate.HMAC_SHA_256
    Implementation of MAC using SHA-256 hash.
    MACImplAlternate.HMAC_SHA1
    Implementation of MAC using SHA-1 hash.
    MACImplAlternate.HMAC_SHA1_96
    Implementation of MAC using SHA1 hash and a block size of 12.
  • Exception Summary 
    Exception Description
    MACException
    Implementation of JSchException for errors relating to the usage of MAC instances.
